\label{defn}A \emph{path decomposition} of a graph $G$ is a sequence of subsets of vertices $(B_1,B_2,\dots,B_r)$ such that \begin{enumerate}[(i)] \item $\bigcup_{1 \leq i \leq r} B_i = V(G)$;\label{i}

\item For all edges $vw \in E(G)$, $\exists~i \in \{1,2,\dots, r\}$ with $v \in B_i$ and $w \in B_i$;\label{ii}

\item For all $i,j,k \in \{1,2,\dots,r\}$, if $i \leq j \leq k$ then $B_i \cap B_k \subseteq B_j$.\label{iii}\end{enumerate}

The \textbf{width} of a path decomposition $(B_1,B_2,\dots,B_r)$ is $ \max_{1 \leq i \leq r} |B_i|-1$, and the \textup{pathwidth} of $G$, denoted $pw(G)$, is the minimum width over all possible path decompositions of $G$.

